\begin_layout Section
Definitions and arithmetic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A vector in three(two) dimensions is an ordered triple(pair) of real numbers.
 The entries in the vector are called its 
\series bold
components
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Vectors add/subtract component-wise: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\left(a_{x},a_{y}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}=\left(b_{x},b_{y}\right)$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}\pm\mathbf{b}=\left(a_{x}\pm b_{x},a_{y}\pm b_{y}\right).
\]

\end_inset

This is true regardless of which unit vectors are used.
 You can visualize it with the parallelogram rule.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication of a vector by a scalar multiplies each component by that
 scalar:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\mathbf{a}=\left(\alpha a_{x},\alpha a_{y}\right).
\]

\end_inset

It 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scales
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the vector by the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha<0$
\end_inset

, the direction is reversed and the magnitude is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\alpha\right|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\series bold
magnitude 
\series default
of a vector is its Pythagorean length:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert =\sqrt{a_{x}^{2}+a_{y}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

in 2D and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert =\sqrt{a_{x}^{2}+a_{y}^{2}+a_{z}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

in 3D.
 Some books with use single bars, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{a}\right|$
\end_inset

, where we use double bars.
 We'll also sometimes write 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 for the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
 When this notation is used it's especially important to use some distinguishing
 notation for vectors; otherwise, you'll quickly become confused between
 the scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In 2D, we can write the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 in polar form as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\cos\phi,a\sin\phi\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the angle from the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis, running CCW.
 There's also a polar form for 3D vectors, but we'll wait on that until
 we've laid some more foundation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Unit vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2D, define 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat=\left(1,0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\jhat=\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then any 2D vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=\left(a_{x},a_{y}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}=a_{x}\ihat+a_{y}\jhat.
\]

\end_inset

In 3D, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat=\left(1,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\jhat=\left(0,1,0\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\khat=\left(0,0,1\right)$
\end_inset

, and we can write any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}=a_{x}\ihat+a_{y}\jhat+a_{z}\khat.
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\jhat$
\end_inset

 system in 2D and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat,\jhat,\khat$
\end_inset

 systems in 3D are orthogonal: 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat\perp\jhat$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat\perp\khat$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\jhat\perp\khat$
\end_inset

.
 Since these vectors also have unit magnitude (they're 
\series bold
normalized
\series default
) we call these systems 
\series bold
orthonormal
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You might also see the symbols 
\begin_inset Formula $\xhat$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\yhat$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zhat$
\end_inset

 in place of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\jhat$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\khat$
\end_inset

.
 When working with generic unit vectors we'll often use the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat$
\end_inset

 (from German 
\emph on
einheit
\emph default
, unit).
 For example, in an orthogonal system of unit vectors we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat_{i}\perp\ehat_{j}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ne j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, we can produce a unit vector in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 by dividing by its magnitude,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\hat{a}}=\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert }.
\]

\end_inset

This procedure is called 
\series bold
normalization
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dot product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dot product takes two vectors as arguments, and returns a scalar.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 are represented in terms of their Cartesian components, define the dot
 product by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=\sum_{j=1}^{3}a_{j}b_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Properties: from the definition you can show that for all vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=\mathbf{b}\cdot\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
the dot product is commutative
\emph default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha\mathbf{a}\right)\cdot\mathbf{b}=\alpha\left(\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
the dot product commutes with scalar multiplication
\emph default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\left(\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}\right)=\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
the dot product distributes over addition
\emph default
)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{a}\ge0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{a}=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}=0$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
the dot product is positive definite)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Properties 2 and 3 can be summed up in a single equation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\left(\beta\mathbf{b}+\gamma\mathbf{c}\right)=\beta\left(\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}\right)+\gamma\left(\mathbf{a}\cdot\text{\textbf{c}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\emph on
Dot products distribute over linear combinations.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{ab}$
\end_inset

 be the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 With the angle addition formula, the dot product can be shown to be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{b}\right\Vert \cos\theta_{ab}.
\]

\end_inset

Consequences: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=0$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\perp\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{a}=\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert ^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cauchy-Schwarz inequality: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}\right|\le\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{b}\right\Vert $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 are represented in arbitrary unit vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=\sum_{i=1}^{3}\sum_{j=1}^{3}a_{i}b_{j}\ehat_{i}\cdot\ehat_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

If those unit vectors are orthonormal (
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat_{i}\cdot\ehat_{j}=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

), then the preceding result simplifies to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=\sum_{j=1}^{3}a_{j}b_{j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Applications of the dot product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal uses of the dot product will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To find the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 along a unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{p}}$
\end_inset

, compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{p}\cdot a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To find the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert =\sqrt{\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To check if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\perp\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, check if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\mathbf{b}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With orthonormal unit vectors, any vector can be resolved into components
 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}=\left(\ehat_{1}\cdot\mathbf{a}\right)\ehat_{1}+\left(\ehat_{2}\cdot\mathbf{a}\right)\ehat_{2}+\left(\ehat_{3}\cdot\mathbf{a}\right)\ehat_{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These have many applications in analyzing the geometry of physical problems.
 Spoiler: we'll develop an abstract generalization of the dot product that
 lets us apply these ideas to 
\emph on
functions
\emph default
 as well as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ordinary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 3D vectors.
 For now, we stick with the concrete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A familiar application: block on an inclined plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You've likely encountered the problem of a block sliding on an inclined
 plane.
 The key step is to resolve the downward gravitational force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{g}$
\end_inset

 into two components: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 down along the plane's surface and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

 normal to it.
 By contemplating triangles you can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

 has magnitude 
\begin_inset Formula $mg\sin\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The distance traveled down a frictionless plane starting from rest is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s\left(t\right)=s_{0}-\frac{1}{2}gt^{2}\sin\alpha.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In more complicated problems it's harder to work out vector components by
 inspection.
 Following the general principle that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
algebra is a way to substitute computation for thinking
\emph default
,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 we'll develop a systematic method for finding components.
 In the inclined plane example, we introduce an orthonormal set of unit
 vectors, a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 down along the plane and a normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{n}}$
\end_inset

 outward from the plane.
 By construction, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}\cdot\hat{n}}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 in terms of these unit vectors,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}=F_{\tau}\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}+F_{n}\boldsymbol{\hat{n}},
\]

\end_inset

where the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{n}$
\end_inset

 are to be determined.
 To find the components along each unit vector, use the dot product.
 Dot 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}\cdot\mathbf{F}=F_{\tau}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}\cdot\hat{\tau}}\right)+F_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}\cdot\hat{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=1F_{\tau}+0F_{n}=F_{\tau},
\]

\end_inset

so we find
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\tau}=\text{\ensuremath{\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}}\ensuremath{\cdot\mathbf{F}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, dot 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{n}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 to find the normal component,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{n}=\boldsymbol{\hat{n}}\cdot\mathbf{F}.
\]

\end_inset

All of this can be represented compactly in the formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}=\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}\cdot\mathbf{F}\right)\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}+\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{n}}\cdot\mathbf{F}\right)\boldsymbol{\hat{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

With 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 appearing on both sides, here's what the formula means: given some 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 and an orthonormal unit vector set , resolve it into components along 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{\tau}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{n}}$
\end_inset

 by taking dot products 
\begin_inset Formula $\tauhat\cdot\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nhat\cdot\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

