\begin_layout Subsubsection
A less familiar application: polarized light
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an electromagnetics course you'll learn that light is a wave in an EM
 field.
 Plane EM waves are transverse: if a plane wave is traveling in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

direction (along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\ihat}$
\end_inset

) then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\perp\ihat$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\perp\ihat$
\end_inset

 , which we can express using the dot product: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\cdot\mathbf{\ihat=}0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\cdot\ihat=0$
\end_inset

.
 It can also be shown that in a plane wave 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}\perp\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

.
 In the rest of this discussion we'll focus on the electric field and ignore
 the magnetic field.
 The polarization state of a wave is the direction of the electric field
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

.
 A typical light source (an LED bulb, a star, etc) emits light that is unpolariz
ed: a superposition of different polarization states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although most (not all!) emitters produce unpolarized light, it is possible
 to obtain polarized light.
 Materials called polarizers transmit only light with a specific polarization
 state, absorbing all else.
 Unpolarized light entering a polarizer emerges polarized.
 Other processes can select for certain polarizations; these include scattering
 and reflection.
 We'll focus on polarizing materials, and consider a polarizer to be a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

black box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that selects a particular polarization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a mathematical model of the action of a polarizer, we need two vectors:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phat$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Resolving a vector into orthogonal components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is important enough to call out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout BoxedImportant
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ehat_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal set of unit vectors in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\RR^{n}$
\end_inset

, then any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\in\RR^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be expanded uniquely as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}F_{j}\ehat_{j},
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{j}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{j}=\ehat_{j}\cdot\mathbf{F}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cross product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 define a parallelogram.
 A direction, or orientation, can be assigned to the parallelogram using
 the right-hand rule: start with your right fingers along 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, curl your fingers into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, and your thumb indicates the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Definition: The cross product 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is the vector in the direction given by the right-hand rule, having magnitude
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{a\times}\mathbf{b}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 equal to the area of the parallelogram.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consequences: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}=-\mathbf{b}\times\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\cdot\left(\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}\right\Vert =\left\Vert \mathbf{a}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{b}\right\Vert \left|\sin\theta_{ab}\right|$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
You can compute the cross product using the determinant formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}\times\mathbf{b}=\left|\begin{array}{ccc}
\ihat & \jhat & \khat\\
a_{x} & a_{y} & a_{z}\\
b_{x} & b_{y} & b_{z}
\end{array}\right|=\left(a_{y}b_{z}-a_{z}b_{y}\right)\ihat-\left(a_{x}b_{z}-a_{z}b_{x}\right)\jhat+\left(a_{x}b_{y}-a_{y}b_{x}\right)\khat.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Orthogonal curvilinear coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle q_{1},q_{2},q_{3}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are orthogonal curvilinear coordinates, then the scale factors 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{j}$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{j}=\left\Vert \pd{\mathbf{r}}{q_{j}}\right\Vert ,
\]

\end_inset

and the unit vectors tangent to the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 coordinate line, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ehat_{j}=\frac{1}{h_{j}}\pd{\mathbf{r}}{q_{j}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-three-most"

\end_inset

The three most important coordinate systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cartesian: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}\left(z,y,z\right)=x\ihat+y\jhat+z\khat$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{x}=h_{y}=h_{z}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Cylindrical polar coordinates: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}\left(\rho,\phi,z\right)=\rho\left(\ihat\cos\phi+\jhat\sin\phi\right)+z\zhat$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\rho}=1$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\rhohat=\ihat\cos\phi+\jhat\sin\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\phi}=\rho$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\phihat=-\ihat\sin\phi+\jhat\cos\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{z}=1$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\zhat=\khat$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=\rho\rhohat+z\zhat$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, the system reduces to 2D polar (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plane polar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) coordinates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Spherical polar coordinates: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}\left(r,\theta,\phi\right)=r\left(\left(\ihat\cos\phi+\jhat\sin\phi\right)\sin\theta+\khat\cos\theta\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{r}=1$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{r}}=\left(\ihat\cos\phi+\jhat\sin\phi\right)\sin\theta+\khat\cos\theta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\theta}=r$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\thetahat=\left(\ihat\cos\phi+\jhat\sin\phi\right)\cos\theta-\khat\sin\theta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\phi}=r\sin\theta$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\phihat=-\ihat\sin\phi+\jhat\cos\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=r\boldsymbol{\hat{r}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Except in Cartesian coordinates, the unit vectors depend on the coordinates.
 One consequence to be explored below is that if a particle's position is
 described in non-Cartesian coordinates, the unit vectors change as the
 particle moves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certainly in cylindrical and possibly in spherical coordinates you can reason
 through the geometry to figure out the unit vectors, and skip the calculation
 of the scale factors and partial derivatives.
 However, the geometrical reasoning gets much more complicated for coordinate
 systems such as ellipsoidal or parabolic coordinates, while the brute force
 calculation will always work.
 The calculation might be complicated, but it's mindless and can be done
 by a computer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Cartesian-to-non-Cartesian"

\end_inset

Cartesian unit vectors represented in non-Cartesian coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's sometimes useful (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:pendulum-equation-of-motion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below) to write the Cartesian unit vectors in terms of unit vectors in
 another system.
 We can do this with dot products: for example, to find the components of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat$
\end_inset

 in the cylindrical unit vectors, write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ihat$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ihat=\left(\ihat\cdot\rhohat\right)\rhohat+\left(\ihat\cdot\phihat\right)\phihat+\left(\ihat\cdot\zhat\right)\zhat
\]

\end_inset

and work through the algebra,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ihat\cdot\rhohat=\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ihat\cdot\phihat=-\sin\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ihat\cdot\zhat=0,
\]

\end_inset

leading to the result
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ihat=\rhohat\cos\phi-\phihat\sin\phi.
\]

\end_inset

A similar calculation finds
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\jhat=\rhohat\sin\phi+\phihat\cos\phi
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\khat=\zhat.
\]

\end_inset

The same procedure can be used to do any transformation between any two
 systems of orthonormal unit vectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Time derivatives of vectors and products
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Differentiate a vector component-by-component:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{\mathbf{f}}{t}=\od{}{t}\left[\sum_{j=1}^{3}f_{j}\left(t\right)\ehat_{j}\left(t\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sum_{j=1}^{3}\od{f_{j}}{t}\ehat_{j}+\sum_{j=1}^{3}f_{j}\od{\ehat_{j}}{t}.
\]

\end_inset

When the unit vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ehat_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 are constant in time, then the second term is zero.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By grinding through the ordinary product rule, you can easily show the following
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{}{t}\left(\alpha\mathbf{f}\right)=\alpha\od{\mathbf{f}}{t}+\od{\alpha}{t}\mathbf{f}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{}{t}\left(\mathbf{f}\cdot\mathbf{g}\right)=\od{\mathbf{f}}{t}\cdot\mathbf{g}+\mathbf{f}\cdot\od{\mathbf{g}}{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{}{t}\left(\mathbf{f}\cdot\mathbf{f}\right)=2\mathbf{f}\cdot\od{\mathbf{f}}{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{}{t}\left(\mathbf{f}\times\mathbf{g}\right)=\od{\mathbf{f}}{t}\times\mathbf{g}+\mathbf{f}\times\od{\mathbf{g}}{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Applications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Angular momentum and torque
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The angular momentum of a particle is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}=m\mathbf{r}\times\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}$
\end_inset

, using the product rule for the cross product:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{\mathbf{L}}{t}=m\od{\mathbf{r}}{t}\times\mathbf{v}+m\mathbf{r}\times\od{\mathbf{v}}{t}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=m\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{r}\times\left(m\mathbf{a}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\mathbf{r}\times\mathbf{F};
\]

\end_inset

this is the familiar relation between angular momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}$
\end_inset

 and torque 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}\times\mathbf{F}$
\end_inset

.
 When the force is entirely radial, the torque is zero, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\mathbf{L}}{t}=0$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{L}=\text{constant}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Motion in a magnetic field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lorentz force on a charged particle in a magnetic field is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}=q\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

; the nonrelativistic equation of motion is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\od{\mathbf{v}}{t}=q\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{B}.
\]

\end_inset

We won't solve this equation now; however, we can deduce some properties
 of the motion even without a full solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The acceleration is 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp$
\end_inset

 to the velocity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The magnitude of the velocity is constant.
 To prove this, compute
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{}{t}\left(\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}\right)=2\mathbf{v}\cdot\od{\mathbf{v}}{t}
\]

\end_inset

and use the equation of motion and vector identities to find the result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Time derivatives of unit vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 be any unit vector.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\ehat}{t}\perp\ehat$
\end_inset

.
 You can prove this using the product rule and the property 
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat\cdot\ehat=1$
\end_inset

.
 Here's how to understand it: if 
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\ehat}{t}$
\end_inset

 had a component along 
\begin_inset Formula $\ehat$
\end_inset

, then its magnitude would change; this is impossible, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\ehat}{t}$
\end_inset

 must be 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp\ehat$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Cartesian coordinates the unit vectors are independent of time.
 In other coordinate systems, this will not be the case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cylindrical coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Differentiate the expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rhohat$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phihat$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zhat$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\rhohat}{t}=-\overdot{\phi}\ihat\sin\phi+\overdot{\phi}\jhat\cos\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\phihat}{t}=-\overdot{\phi}\ihat\cos\phi-\overdot{\phi}\jhat\sin\phi$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\od{\zhat}{t}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You'll usually want these in terms of the cylindrical unit vectors.
 By inspection, you can spot that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\od{\rhohat}{t}=\overdot{\phi}\phihat\\
\od{\phihat}{t}=-\overdot{\phi}\rhohat
\end{gather*}

\end_inset

In more complicated coordinate systems it won't be so easy to spot the expansion
 coefficients, but it's always possible to work them out using the dot product:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{\rhohat}{t}=\left(\rhohat\cdot\od{\rhohat}{t}\right)\rhohat+\left(\phihat\cdot\od{\phihat}{t}\right)\phihat
\]

\end_inset

which you can show is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overdot{\phi}\phihat$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In mechanics, we'll also want the second derivatives (used in accelerations).
 The hard part was computing the first derivatives; with those in hand,
 it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\odd{\rhohat}{t}=\overddot{\phi}\phihat-\overdot{\phi}^{2}\rhohat\\
\odd{\phihat}{t}=-\overddot{\phi}\rhohat-\overdot{\phi}^{2}\phihat
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Newton's second law in cylindrical coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a particle with constant mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, Newton's second law of motion is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\odd{\mathbf{r}}{t}=\mathbf{F}.
\]

\end_inset

In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-three-most"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we saw that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}=\rho\rhohat+z\zhat$
\end_inset

.
 The acceleration is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\odd{\mathbf{r}}{t}=\overddot{\rho}\rhohat+2\overdot{\rho}\od{\rhohat}{t}+\rho\odd{\rhohat}{t}+\overddot{z}\zhat
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\left(\overddot{\rho}-\rho\overdot{\phi}^{2}\right)\rhohat+\left(\rho\overddot{\phi}+2\overdot{\rho}\overdot{\phi}\right)\phihat+\overddot{z}\zhat.
\]

\end_inset

The equations of motion are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\left(\overddot{\rho}-\rho\overdot{\phi}^{2}\right)=F_{\rho}=\rhohat\cdot\mathbf{F}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\left(\rho\overddot{\phi}+2\overdot{\rho}\overdot{\phi}\right)=F_{\phi}=\phihat\cdot\mathbf{F}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\overddot{z}=F_{z}=\zhat\cdot\mathbf{F}.
\]

\end_inset

This is a system of three coupled second order differential equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Angular momentum conservation again
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The angular equation of motion is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\left(\rho\overddot{\phi}+2\overdot{\rho}\overdot{\phi}\right)=F_{\phi}.
\]

\end_inset

This is a second order differential equation involving both 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

; it can't be solved without also solving the other two equations of motion.
 But notice that if we introduce 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}=m\rho^{2}\overdot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 and differentiate
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{}{t}\left(m\rho^{2}\overdot{\phi}\right)=m\rho^{2}\overddot{\phi}+2m\rho\overdot{\phi}\overdot{\rho},
\]

\end_inset

we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\od{L_{z}}{t}=\rho F_{\phi}.
\]

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\phi}=0$
\end_inset

, the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{z}$
\end_inset

 is constant in time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Uniform circular motion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider uniform circular motion in the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, centered on the origin.
 Cylindrical coordinates are the obvious choice for this problem; the radial
 coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 remains constant while the angular coordinate varies linearly with time,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(t\right)=a;\;\;\;\phi\left(t\right)=\omega t+\phi_{0};\;\;\;z\left(t\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overdot{\rho}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overddot{\rho}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\overdot{\phi}=\omega$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overddot{\phi}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Plug into the equations of motion, finding 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-m\rho\omega^{2}=F_{\rho}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\phi}=0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{z}=0.
\]

\end_inset

The first of these equations is the well-known condition for the centripetal
 force required to hold a particle in circular motion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:pendulum-equation-of-motion"

\end_inset

Equation of motion of an ideal pendulum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It will be convenient work in the 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y$
\end_inset

 plane but to orient the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis downwards and the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis pointing to the right.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the angle (CCW) from the downward vertical, and the gravitational force
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}=mg\ihat$
\end_inset

.
 Cylindrical coordinates are the natural choice: the pendulum moves, the
 radial coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 remains constant and the angular coordinate varies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forces on the pendulum are gravitational, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{\text{grav}}=mg\ihat$
\end_inset

, and an unknown, variable, tension in the pendulum rod, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}_{\text{tens}}=F_{\text{tens}}\rhohat$
\end_inset

.
 Since we're working in cylindrical coordinates, use the method of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Cartesian-to-non-Cartesian"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to write the gravitational force as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}_{\text{grav}}=mg\rhohat\cos\phi-mg\phihat\sin\phi.
\]

\end_inset

In an ideal pendulum, the tension is a 
\emph on
constraint
\emph default
 that will be chosen to keep the length of the pendulum rod constant.
 The total force is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{F}=\left(mg\cos\phi+F_{\text{tens}}\right)\rhohat-mg\phihat\sin\phi
\]

\end_inset

Write out the equations of motion (ignoring the unused coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\left(\overddot{\rho}-\rho\overdot{\phi}^{2}\right)=mg\cos\phi+F_{\text{tens}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\left(\rho\overddot{\phi}+2\overdot{\rho}\overdot{\phi}\right)=-mg\sin\phi.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

, these simplify to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-m\ell\overdot{\phi}^{2}=mg\cos\phi+F_{\text{tens}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m\ell\overddot{\phi}=-mg\sin\phi.
\]

\end_inset

These are two differential equations with, apparently, only one unknown:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 However, the tension 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\text{tens}}$
\end_inset

 is a free variable that we choose to maintain a perfact balance with the
 radial component of gravity and the fictitious radial force 
\begin_inset Formula $m\ell\overdot{\phi}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The first equation is then satisfied by assumption, leaving the equation
 of motion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overddot{\phi}=-\frac{g}{\ell}\sin\phi.
\]

\end_inset

This equation is nonlinear and can't be solved exactly in closed form; a
 useful approach when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\phi\right|\ll1$
\end_inset

 is to use the small angle approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\phi\approx\phi$
\end_inset

 to derive a linear equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overddot{\phi}=-\frac{g}{\ell}\phi.
\]

\end_inset

This is the harmonic oscillator equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\overddot{\phi}+\omega_{0}^{2}\phi=0$
\end_inset

 with natural frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=\sqrt{g/\ell}$
\end_inset

; we'll study this in great depth in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "chap:Second-order-ordinary-differenti"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For now, recall from elementary physics that the solution to the simple
 harmonic oscillator equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\left(t\right)=A\cos\left(\omega_{0}t+\delta_{0}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where the amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 are found from the initial conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The period of the motion (in the small angle approximation only) is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T=\frac{2\pi}{\omega_{0}}=2\pi\sqrt{\frac{\ell}{g}}.
\]

\end_inset

You will see later how to derive corrections to this formula when the amplitude
 is large enough that the small angle approximation is no longer valid.
 
\end_layout

